---
import Article from '../../../layouts/Article.astro';
import Fig from '../../../components/Fig.astro';
import Callout from '../../../components/Callout.astro';
import DataTable from '../../../components/DataTable.astro';
import FaqBlock from '../../../components/FaqBlock.astro';
import CtaButton from '../../../components/CtaButton.astro';
import { getFits, getRebates, getState, getSystems } from '../../../lib/data';
import {
  calculateFederalRebate,
  dollarsPerUsableKwh,
  formatAud,
  formatDateLong,
} from '../../../lib/rebate';

const rebates = getRebates();
const wa = getState('wa')!;
const systems = getSystems();
const fits = getFits().states.find((s) => s.code === 'wa')!;
const perKwh = dollarsPerUsableKwh(rebates);
const ref = systems.systems.find((s) => s.id === '13-5kwh')!;
const federal = calculateFederalRebate(ref.usableKwh, rebates);

const synergy = wa.schemes.find((s) => s.name.includes('Synergy'))!;
const horizon = wa.schemes.find((s) => s.name.includes('Horizon'))!;

function stateAmount(
  scheme: (typeof wa.schemes)[0],
  usableKwh: number,
): number {
  if (scheme.value.kind === 'perKwh') {
    const raw = usableKwh * scheme.value.amount;
    return scheme.cap != null ? Math.min(raw, scheme.cap) : raw;
  }
  return scheme.value.amount;
}

const synergyAmt = stateAmount(synergy, ref.usableKwh);
const horizonAmt = stateAmount(horizon, ref.usableKwh);
const synergyTotal = federal.federalRebate + synergyAmt;
const horizonTotal = federal.federalRebate + horizonAmt;
const synergyNet = ref.typicalInstalledCost - synergyTotal;
const horizonNet = ref.typicalInstalledCost - horizonTotal;

const schemeRows = wa.schemes.map((s) => [
  s.name,
  s.value.kind === 'perKwh'
    ? `${formatAud(s.value.amount)} / ${s.value.unit}`
    : formatAud(s.value.amount),
  s.cap != null ? formatAud(s.cap) : '—',
  s.stacksWithFederal ? 'Yes' : 'No',
  s.status,
]);

const faq = [
  {
    question: 'Do I get both the federal and WA rebates?',
    answer:
      'Yes when you meet both sets of rules. The federal Cheaper Home Batteries discount is usually applied by your installer at point of sale. The WA Residential Battery Scheme is a separate state payment with its own Synergy or Horizon pathway — stacking is allowed on both streams we list.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Am I on Synergy or Horizon Power?',
    answer:
      'Most of the Perth and South West Interconnected System (SWIS) is Synergy. Horizon Power covers regional and remote networks. Check a recent bill — the retailer name determines which WA per-kWh rate and cap apply.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is DEBS and how does it affect battery maths?',
    answer:
      'The Distributed Energy Buyback Scheme sets Synergy’s export payments by time band. Midday exports often pay little; evening bands pay more. A battery that shifts your own evening load usually beats exporting cheap midday kWh — that is the core WA payback story, not a guaranteed FiT.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Do I need existing solar?',
    answer:
      'WA scheme eligibility listed here requires existing or simultaneous rooftop solar for the Synergy stream, plus a CEC-approved battery and an accredited installer. Confirm the live checklist on the WA Government / Energy Policy WA pages before you sign.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Are Perth install prices the same as the east coast?',
    answer:
      'Not always. Freight, installer utilisation, and product mix move Perth quotes. Use our typical installed costs as a planning band, then collect local quotes — the rebate maths still starts from usable kWh and your retailer.',
  },
];

const description = `WA battery rebates that stack with the federal discount. Synergy vs Horizon rates, DEBS context, and a ${ref.usableKwh} kWh stacking example. Federal tier 1 about $${perKwh.toFixed(0)}/kWh.`;
---

<Article
  title="WA battery rebate: what stacks with the federal discount"
  description={description}
  crumbs={[
    { label: 'Home', href: '/' },
    { label: 'Battery rebate', href: '/battery-rebate/' },
    { label: 'Western Australia' },
  ]}
  updated="2026-07-12"
  verified={rebates.meta.lastVerified}
>
  <Fragment slot="toc">
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#federal">Federal discount first</a></li>
      <li><a href="#schemes">WA schemes</a></li>
      <li><a href="#synergy-horizon">Synergy vs Horizon</a></li>
      <li><a href="#debs">DEBS and feed-in</a></li>
      <li><a href="#stacking">13.5 kWh stacking example</a></li>
      <li><a href="#perth-costs">Perth install costs</a></li>
      <li><a href="#eligibility">Eligibility</a></li>
      <li><a href="#sources">Sources</a></li>
    </ul>
  </Fragment>

  <p>
    Western Australia is where federal and state battery support actually meet on a typical household
    quote. The Cheaper Home Batteries Program currently pays about <Fig>{formatAud(perKwh)}</Fig> per
    usable kWh in the first tier (verified {formatDateLong(rebates.meta.lastVerified)}). On top of that,
    the WA Residential Battery Scheme pays a separate per-kWh amount that differs for Synergy customers
    on the SWIS and Horizon Power customers in regional networks — both streams stack with the federal
    discount when eligibility holds.
  </p>

  <h2 id="federal">Federal discount first</h2>
  <p>
    Every eligible WA home starts with the same national rules: CEC-approved battery, accredited
    installer, usable capacity in the program’s nominal range, and — for grid-connected systems —
    VPP-capable hardware where required. Since <Fig>1 May 2026</Fig> the federal payment uses three
    tiers ending at <Fig>{rebates.current.usableCapCapKwh}</Fig> kWh usable. Install date sets the rate.
  </p>
  <p>
    For our reference <Fig>{ref.usableKwh}</Fig> kWh system, the federal rebate at current assumptions is{' '}
    <Fig>{formatAud(federal.federalRebate)}</Fig> (
    <Fig>{federal.stcCount}</Fig> STCs × <Fig>{formatAud(rebates.stcPrice.netAssumed)}</Fig>). That
    figure is the floor of the stacking maths below — state money sits on top, it does not replace it.
  </p>

  <h2 id="schemes">WA schemes at a glance</h2>
  <DataTable
    caption={`WA battery schemes (verified ${formatDateLong(synergy.lastVerified)})`}
    headers={['Scheme', 'Value', 'Cap', 'Stacks federally', 'Status']}
    rows={schemeRows}
    numericCols={[1, 2]}
  />
  <p>
    Synergy’s listed rate is <Fig>{formatAud(synergy.value.amount)}</Fig> per usable kWh capped at{' '}
    <Fig>{formatAud(synergy.cap!)}</Fig>. Horizon’s listed rate is{' '}
    <Fig>{formatAud(horizon.value.amount)}</Fig> per usable kWh capped at{' '}
    <Fig>{formatAud(horizon.cap!)}</Fig>. Higher Horizon support reflects greater network value in
    regional and remote systems — it is not a Perth metro rate.
  </p>

  <h2 id="synergy-horizon">Synergy vs Horizon: which bucket are you in?</h2>
  <p>
    If you live in greater Perth, Mandurah, or most of the south-west grid, you are almost certainly a
    Synergy customer on the SWIS. Horizon Power is the vertically integrated utility for many towns and
    remote networks outside that grid. The WA scheme splits because the network benefit of a residential
    battery is different in each footprint.
  </p>
  <p>
    Practically: pull a recent electricity bill. If it says Synergy, use the Synergy row and the{' '}
    <Fig>{formatAud(synergy.cap!)}</Fig> cap. If it says Horizon Power, use the Horizon row. Do not
    average the two — installers will not.
  </p>

  <Callout type="warning" title="Rates marked verify">
    <p>
      Seed values in our data file carry a verify flag until launch sign-off against Energy Policy WA /
      Horizon primary pages. Always confirm the live per-kWh figure and cap on the government source
      linked below before you treat a quote as final.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="debs">DEBS feed-in context</h2>
  <p>
    Synergy’s Distributed Energy Buyback Scheme (DEBS) pays for exported solar by time band. Our FiT
    snapshot for WA currently spans about <Fig>{fits.minCPerKwh}</Fig>–
    <Fig>{fits.maxCPerKwh}</Fig> c/kWh across reference offers (verified{' '}
    {formatDateLong(fits.lastVerified)}). Midday exports are often at the bottom of that range; evening
    bands are higher — but still a fraction of the retail import rate you avoid by self-consuming.
  </p>
  <p>
    That is why batteries show up in WA payback conversations even when the export tariff looks “fine”
    on paper. Shifting your own evening cooking and air-con load displaces expensive imports. Exporting
    surplus at a few cents is the leftover, not the plan. See also our{' '}
    <a href="/feed-in-tariffs/">feed-in tariff overview</a> and{' '}
    <a href="/guides/is-a-battery-worth-it/">is a battery worth it?</a> guide.
  </p>

  <h2 id="stacking">Worked stacking example: {ref.usableKwh} kWh</h2>
  <p>
    Using the site’s Powerwall-class reference system (
    <Fig>{ref.label}</Fig>, typical installed cost <Fig>{formatAud(ref.typicalInstalledCost)}</Fig>
    ):
  </p>
  <DataTable
    caption="13.5 kWh stacking — federal + WA scheme"
    headers={['Component', 'Synergy customer', 'Horizon customer']}
    rows={[
      ['Federal rebate', formatAud(federal.federalRebate), formatAud(federal.federalRebate)],
      ['WA scheme', formatAud(synergyAmt), formatAud(horizonAmt)],
      ['Combined support', formatAud(synergyTotal), formatAud(horizonTotal)],
      ['Illustrative net cost', formatAud(synergyNet), formatAud(horizonNet)],
    ]}
    numericCols={[1, 2]}
  />
  <p>
    Notice the WA lines hit the cap: <Fig>{ref.usableKwh}</Fig> × Synergy’s per-kWh rate exceeds{' '}
    <Fig>{formatAud(synergy.cap!)}</Fig>, so the state payment stops at the cap. Same pattern for
    Horizon at <Fig>{formatAud(horizon.cap!)}</Fig>. Oversizing past the federal full-rate band (14 kWh)
    does not unlock more state dollars once the cap is reached.
  </p>

  <h2 id="perth-costs">Perth install-cost note</h2>
  <p>
    Perth quotes for a mid-size battery commonly land in a band around the reference{' '}
    <Fig>{formatAud(ref.typicalInstalledCost)}</Fig> before rebates, but site works, inverter pairing,
    three-phase upgrades, and product choice move that number. Freight into WA and installer diaries also
    matter. Treat published “from” prices as marketing floors; the stacking table above is for comparing
    support dollars, not for locking a contract price.
  </p>
  <p>
    For a package view that includes panels, see{' '}
    <a href="/costs/solar-battery-package-perth/">solar + battery package costs in Perth</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="eligibility">Eligibility checklist (both layers)</h2>
  <h3>Federal</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Battery on the CEC-approved list for the program</li>
    <li>Accredited installer; one system per property under program rules</li>
    <li>Usable / nominal capacity within the published eligible range</li>
    <li>Grid-connected systems: VPP-capable where required</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>WA Synergy stream</h3>
  <ul>
    {synergy.eligibility.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}
  </ul>
  <h3>WA Horizon stream</h3>
  <ul>
    {horizon.eligibility.map((item) => <li>{item}</li>)}
  </ul>

  <p>
    <CtaButton href="/battery-rebate/calculator/">Calculate my federal rebate</CtaButton>
  </p>

  <h2 id="sources">Sources</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href={rebates.meta.sourceUrl}>{rebates.meta.program}</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={synergy.sourceUrl}>{synergy.name}</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={horizon.sourceUrl}>{horizon.name}</a>
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href={fits.sourceUrl}>Synergy / DEBS reference</a>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <FaqBlock items={faq} />
</Article>
